Question 2:

Instructions: Create two new categorical variables in flights based on the departure time (dep_time), and arrival time (arr_time). These new variables should have four categories: âearly morningâ for 12am to 6am, âmorningâ for 6am to 12pm, âafternoonâ for 12pm to 6pm, and âeveningâ for 6pm to 12am. Show barplots of both of these new variables. What percentage of flights were âred eyeâ flights?

#step 1: convert HHMM to hours (for instance, 523 -> 5.38 is 5h23m)
time_to_hour <- function(x) {
  ifelse(is.na(x), NA,
         floor(x / 100) + (x %% 100) / 60)}

#step 2: Add categorical variables for dep_time and arr_time
flights_timecat <- flights %>%
  mutate(dep_hour = time_to_hour(dep_time),
         arr_hour = time_to_hour(arr_time),
         dep_hour = case_when(
           dep_hour >= 0  & dep_hour < 6  ~ "early morning",
           dep_hour >= 6  & dep_hour < 12 ~ "morning",
           dep_hour >= 12 & dep_hour < 18 ~ "afternoon",
           dep_hour >= 18 & dep_hour < 24 ~ "evening",
           TRUE ~ NA_character_
         ),
         arr_hour = case_when(
           arr_hour >= 0  & arr_hour < 6  ~ "early morning",
           arr_hour >= 6  & arr_hour < 12 ~ "morning",
           arr_hour >= 12 & arr_hour < 18 ~ "afternoon",
           arr_hour >= 18 & arr_hour < 24 ~ "evening",
           TRUE ~ NA_character_
         ))
##step 3: show barplots for the variables
# Plot departure time
ggplot(flights_timecat, aes(x = dep_hour)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "steelblue") +
  labs(title = "Number of Flights by Departure",
       x = "Departure time",
       y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal()
# Plot arrival time
ggplot(flights_timecat, aes(x = arr_hour)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "darkblue") +
  labs(title = "Number of Flights by Arrival",
       x = "Arrival time",
       y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal()
#step 4: Define red-eye flights
flights_timecat <- flights_timecat %>%
  mutate(red_eye = dep_hour %in% c("afternoon", "evening") &
                     arr_hour %in% c("early morning", "morning"))

#step 5: Calculate percentage of red-eye flights
red_eye_pct <- flights_timecat %>%
  summarise(percent_red_eye = mean(red_eye, na.rm = TRUE) * 100)
red_eye_pct

The weather data also includes a minute column, but by only adding hour to the key variable, we are collapsing all observations that correspond to the same hour.

Instructions: Now merge the flights data and the weather data so that each flight contains information about the weather at its departure airport at the time it was scheduled to take off. Youâll want to use the variables time_hour and origin in order to do this.

flights_weather <- flights %>%
  left_join(
    weather_unique %>%
      distinct(origin, time_hour, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%
      select(-year, -month, -day, -hour), #this is to avoid duplicates on year, month, day, and hour from both datasets (example year.y and year.x, only shows year)
    by = c("origin", "time_hour")
  )

#1) Define weather conditions on the merged flights_weather data. The FAA and National Weather Service (NWS) define impact thresholds meaningful for flights. We need to set up the following conditions, otherwise higher values will lead to misinterpretations. 
low_press_cut <- quantile(flights_weather$pressure, 0.10, na.rm = TRUE)

flights_weather_flags <- flights_weather %>%
  mutate(
    Any_precip   = precip > 0,
    Heavy_precip = precip >= 0.5,   # heavy precipitation
    low_vis      = visib <= 2,      # low visibility
    High_wind    = wind_speed >= 20, 
    High_gust    = wind_gust >= 35,
    freezing     = temp <= 32,      # freezing temperature (Â°F)
    low_pressure = pressure <= low_press_cut,
    High_humid   = humid >= 90      # high humidity/moist air
  )

# 2) List of weather conditions
weather_flags <- c("Any_precip","Heavy_precip","low_vis","High_wind",
                   "High_gust","freezing","low_pressure","High_humid")

# 3) Compute correlations between dep_delay and each condition
cor_flags <- flights_weather_flags %>%
  select(dep_delay, all_of(weather_flags)) %>%
  filter(!is.na(dep_delay)) %>%
  summarise(across(all_of(weather_flags),
                   ~ cor(dep_delay, as.numeric(.), use = "complete.obs"))) %>%
  pivot_longer(everything(),
               names_to = "Weather_Flag",
               values_to = "Correlation")

# 4) Plot the flag correlations to see what wheather conditions contribute the most to delayed departures.
ggplot(cor_flags,
       aes(x = reorder(Weather_Flag, Correlation),
           y = Correlation,
           fill = Correlation)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip() +
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "red", mid = "white", high = "blue", midpoint = 0) +
  labs(
    title = "Correlation between Departure Delay and Weather Conditions",
    x = "Weather that impact flights by FAA guidance",
    y = "Correlation (r)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

  • Interpretation: precipitations is the weather condition associated with most flight delays. However, the correlations are not that strong (between -0.1 and +0.12) meaning no single weather condition strongly predicts departure delays; rather I would suggest based in this data that a combination of these weather conditions have greater predictions on flight delays.

library(dplyr)

weather_conditions <- c("temp", "dewp", "humid", "wind_speed",
                  "wind_gust", "precip", "pressure", "visib")

stat_mode <- function(x) {
  x <- x[!is.na(x)]
  if (length(x) == 0) return(NA_real_)
  ux <- unique(x)
  ux[which.max(tabulate(match(x, ux)))]
}

# summary statistics
dep_delay_summary <- map_dfr(weather_conditions, function(v) {
  flights_weather %>%
    filter(!is.na(dep_delay), !is.na(.data[[v]])) %>%
    group_by(Weather_Variable = v, origin) %>%
    summarise(
      n                = n(),
      mean_dep_delay   = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
      median_dep_delay = median(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
      mode_dep_delay   = stat_mode(dep_delay),
      sd_dep_delay     = sd(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
      .groups = "drop"
    )
})

q1 <- quantile(flights_weather$dep_delay, 0.25, na.rm = TRUE)
q3 <- quantile(flights_weather$dep_delay, 0.75, na.rm = TRUE)

upper_bound <- q3 + 1.5 * iqr

library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)
library(ggplot2)

# 1) Define weather conditions on flights_weather
low_press_cut <- quantile(flights_weather$pressure, 0.10, na.rm = TRUE)

weather_cond <- flights_weather %>%
  mutate(
    Any_precip   = precip > 0,
    Heavy_precip = precip >= 0.5,   
    low_vis      = visib <= 2,      
    High_wind    = wind_speed >= 20,
    High_gust    = wind_gust >= 35,
    freezing     = temp <= 32,    
    low_pressure = pressure <= low_press_cut,
    High_humidity   = humid >= 90      
  )

weather_flags <- c("Any_precip","Heavy_precip","low_vis","High_wind",
                   "High_gust","freezing","low_pressure","High_humidity")

# 2) Correlations between dep_delay and weather conditions by origin
cor_by_origin_flags <- weather_cond %>%
  filter(!is.na(dep_delay)) %>%
  group_by(origin) %>%
  summarise(
    across(
      all_of(weather_flags),
      ~ cor(dep_delay, as.numeric(.), use = "complete.obs"),
      .names = "{.col}_cor"
    ),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = ends_with("_cor"),
    names_to = "Weather_Flag",
    values_to = "Correlation"
  ) %>%
  mutate(Weather_Flag = sub("_cor", "", Weather_Flag))

print(cor_by_origin_flags)

Question 8:

Instructions: Compute the average delay by destination, then add that information to the airports data frame. Make a map showing the spatial distribution of delays (you can make it however you like, but we recommend using either ggplot or leaflet). Use the color of the points to display the average delay for each airport.

library(dplyr)
library(leaflet)

# 1) Average DEPARTURE delay by destination
avg_delay_dest <- flights %>%
  group_by(dest) %>%
  summarise(
    avg_dep_delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
    n = n(),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(avg_dep_delay))

# 2) Join to airports (dest -> airports$faa)
airports_delay <- airports %>%
  select(faa, name, lat, lon) %>%
  inner_join(avg_delay_dest, by = c("faa" = "dest")) %>%
  filter(!is.na(lat), !is.na(lon))

pal <- colorNumeric("RdYlBu", domain = airports_delay$avg_dep_delay, reverse = TRUE)

leaflet(airports_delay) |>
  addTiles() |>
  addCircleMarkers(
    lng = ~lon, lat = ~lat,
    radius = ~pmax(3, pmin(12, sqrt(n)/4)),   
    fillColor = ~pal(avg_dep_delay),          
    fillOpacity = 0.85,
    stroke = FALSE,
    label = ~paste0(name, " (", faa, "): ",
                    round(avg_dep_delay, 1), " min; n=", n)
  ) |>
  addLegend("bottomright", pal = pal, values = ~avg_dep_delay,
            title = "Mean Departure Delay in Min", opacity =1)
avg_delay_dest <- flights %>%
  group_by(dest) %>%
  summarise(
    avg_arr_delay = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
    n = n(),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(avg_arr_delay))

airports_delay <- airports %>%
  select(faa, name, lat, lon) %>%

Question 9:

Instructions: Create as many plots and summary statistics as needed to answer the primary question above.

library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)
library(ggplot2)

# 1) Define cutoff for "low pressure" (10th percentile)
low_press_cut <- quantile(flights_weather$pressure, 0.10, na.rm = TRUE)

# 2) Create weather condition flags
flights_weather_flags <- flights_weather %>%
  mutate(
    Any_precip   = !is.na(precip) & precip > 0,       # any precipitation
    Heavy_precip = !is.na(precip) & precip >= 0.5,    # heavy precipitation
    low_vis      = !is.na(visib) & visib <= 2,        # low visibility (<= 2 miles)
    High_wind    = !is.na(wind_speed) & wind_speed >= 20,  # high sustained wind
    High_gust    = !is.na(wind_gust) & wind_gust >= 35,    # high gusts
    freezing     = !is.na(temp) & temp <= 32,         # freezing temperatures (Â°F)
    low_pressure = !is.na(pressure) & pressure <= low_press_cut, # low barometric pressure
    High_humid   = !is.na(humid) & humid >= 90        # high humidity (>= 90%)
  )

# 3) List of all weather condition flags
weather_flags <- c(
  "Any_precip",
  "Heavy_precip",
  "low_vis",
  "High_wind",
  "High_gust",
  "freezing",
  "low_pressure",
  "High_humid"
)
# 4) Summarize mean dep_delay for each weather condition
weather_delay_summary <- flights_weather_flags %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = all_of(weather_flags),
    names_to = "Weather_Condition",
    values_to = "Condition_Flag"
  ) %>%
  filter(Condition_Flag == TRUE, !is.na(dep_delay)) %>%
  group_by(Weather_Condition) %>%
  summarise(
    n_flights   = n(),
    mean_delay  = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
    median_delay = median(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd_delay    = sd(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>%
  arrange(desc(mean_delay))

Conclusion: Although any kind of precipitations occurred more frequently and contributed most broadly as shown in problem 6, heavy precipitations in particular caused the most delays in time when occurred. Thus, I showed not only the average impact in frequency but also in time (the longest delays) on flight delays.
